Enumeration

You need to see what ports are open on the victim machine.
Instead of nmap you can use rustscan.

RustScan

RustScan is a modern, fast, and efficient port scanner built using the Rust programming language. It aims to be significantly faster than traditional port scanners like Nmap, especially for large-scale scans, by leveraging Rusts performance and concurrency features.

Key Features

  • Blazing fast: Scans thousands of ports in seconds.

  • Parallelism: Utilizes multiple threads to maximize scanning speed.

  • Nmap integration: Automatically hands off discovered ports to Nmap for detailed service/version detection.

  • Low resource usage: Lightweight and efficient.

Enumerating the victim

rustscan -b 2500 -a 10.10.22.212 -t 2000 --ulimit 5000 -- -A -sC -sV --script vuln
The Modern Day Port Scanner.

: http://discord.skerritt.blog :
: https://github.com/RustScan/RustScan :

RustScan: Because guessing isn't hacking.

Domain

You can see the domain on the resulls:
Domain: windcorp.thm0

#Attacking_Machine
Add the domain to the /etc/hosts file.

10.10.22.212 windcorp.thm0

Web Server

Visit http://windcorp.thm0/.

Look for the technologies with Wappalizer.

Click on the Reset Password button.

You'll see a subdomain page you can't reach.

Subdomain

#Attacking_Machine
Add the subdomain fire.windcorp.thm to /etc/hosts.

Reload the page.
